<subSubSection id="F0C96572FFBAFFFDFEF4901AFEAABEF5" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" type="description">
<paragraph id="B86C36F9FFBAFFFDFEF4901AFDEFBD17" blockId="4.[162,738,1311,1367]" box="[296,604,1343,1367]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">
<heading id="E3248195FFBAFFFDFEF4901AFDEFBD17" box="[296,604,1343,1367]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" reason="4">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFEF4901AFE7EBD15" bold="true" box="[296,461,1343,1367]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">NOV. SP. NOV.</emphasis>
IN 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFE2B9067FDEFBD17" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[503,604,1343,1367]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="707" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Apoidea">APOIDEA</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B86C36F9FFBAFFFDFF529037FF68BE5D" blockId="4.[142,758,1391,1904]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFF529037FE00BDC7" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[142,435,1391,1413]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFF529037FE00BDC7" box="[142,435,1391,1413]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Palaeomacropis eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an ST bee because of its similar cylindrical labial palpal segments (
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFD5F90D6FF7BBD81" author="Michener CD" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" refId="ref5917" refString="Michener CD. 2000. The bees of the world. Baltimore, MD: The Johns Hopkins University Press." type="book" year="2000">Michener, 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Thus, 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFEF990F5FE1BBD80" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[293,424,1453,1474]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFEF990F5FE1BBD80" box="[293,424,1453,1474]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not a 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFDCA90F5FD1DBD81" baseAuthorityName="Nel &amp; Petrulevicius" baseAuthorityYear="2003" box="[534,686,1453,1475]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Megachilidae</taxonomicName>
or an 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFF529093FF53BDA3" baseAuthorityName="Michener" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[142,224,1483,1505]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Apidae</taxonomicName>
. The attribution to a precise taxon within ST bees is complicated by the poor preservation of the glossa.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B86C36F9FFBAFFFDFF7B937FFEAABEF5" blockId="4.[142,758,1391,1904]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFF7B937FFE79BE7F" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[167,458,1575,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFF7B937FFE79BE7F" box="[167,458,1575,1597]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Palaeomacropis eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be included in the Australian family 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFEB8931EFE48BE1E" authorityName="McGinley" authorityYear="1980" box="[356,507,1606,1628]" class="Insecta" family="Stenotritidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Stenotritidae</taxonomicName>
because of its antennal structure. The first flagellar segment of 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFDA2933DFF05BEDB" authorityName="McGinley" authorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Stenotritidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Stenotritidae</taxonomicName>
is longer than the scape, unlike the case of 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFF5293FBFEA2BEFA" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[142,273,1699,1720]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFF5293FBFEA2BEFA" box="[142,273,1699,1720]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F0C96572FFBAFFFDFF7B9399FBEEBBD9" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="B86C36F9FFBAFFFDFF7B9399FC6FBA86" blockId="4.[142,758,1391,1904]" lastBlockId="4.[806,1422,195,1904]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFF7B9399FE7ABE94" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[167,457,1729,1750]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFF7B9399FE7ABE94" box="[167,457,1729,1750]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Palaeomacropis eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not have glossa with bifid apex. This would exclude it from 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFDE69387FD02BEB7" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint Fargeau" authorityYear="1841" box="[570,689,1759,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Colletidae</taxonomicName>
. However, Xeromelissinae (
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFE5A93A6FE48BF56" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint Fargeau" authorityYear="1841" box="[390,507,1790,1812]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Colletidae</taxonomicName>
) has the same kind of metasomal setae as 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFEA09245FDB3BF70" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[380,512,1821,1842]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFEA09245FDB3BF70" box="[380,512,1821,1842]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It has long, erect to suberect setae on S1, S2, S3, S4, and S5, distinctly longer on S2 than on the other sterna (
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFD5F9202FCD3B89B" author="Michener CD" box="[643,864,195,1904]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" refId="ref5917" refString="Michener CD. 2000. The bees of the world. Baltimore, MD: The Johns Hopkins University Press." type="book" year="2000">Michener, 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Xeromelissinae is strictly Neotropical, with two fossils currently included in this group, 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFAFA95BAFAFDB954" authority="Engel, 2000" authorityName="Engel" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Chilicola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="electrodominicana" subGenus="Hylaeosoma">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFAFA95BAFA3EB8B5" box="[1318,1421,226,247]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Chilicola</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFCF29459FC0BB954" box="[814,952,257,278]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Hylaeosoma</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFC099459FB16B954" box="[981,1189,257,278]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">electrodominicana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFB669459FAFDB954" author="Engel MS" box="[1210,1358,257,279]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="1 - 11" refId="ref5550" refString="Engel MS. 2000. A new interpretation of the oldest Fossil Bee (Hymenoptera: Apidae). American Museum Novitates 3296: 1 - 11." type="journal article" year="2000">Engel, 2000</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFCFA9447FAB9B977" authority="Michener &amp; Poinar, 1996" authorityName="Michener &amp; Poinar" authorityYear="1996" box="[806,1290,287,309]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Chilicola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFCFA9447FC5BB976" box="[806,1000,287,308]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Chilicola gracilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFC339447FAB9B977" author="Michener CD &amp; Poinar G" box="[1007,1290,287,309]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="353 - 361" refId="ref6040" refString="Michener CD, Poinar G. 1996. The known bee fauna of the Dominican amber. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society 69: 353 - 361." type="journal article" year="1996">Michener &amp; Poinar, 1996</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, both found in Dominican amber (
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFBC09466FA89B916" author="Michener CD &amp; Poinar G" box="[1052,1338,318,340]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="353 - 361" refId="ref6040" refString="Michener CD, Poinar G. 1996. The known bee fauna of the Dominican amber. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society 69: 353 - 361." type="journal article" year="1996">Michener &amp; Poinar, 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFA999466FCD3B931" author="Engel MS" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="1 - 11" refId="ref5550" refString="Engel MS. 2000. A new interpretation of the oldest Fossil Bee (Hymenoptera: Apidae). American Museum Novitates 3296: 1 - 11." type="journal article" year="2000">Engel, 2000</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFCAF9405FB24B930" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[883,1175,349,370]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFCAF9405FB24B930" box="[883,1175,349,370]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Palaeomacropis eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the Xeromelissinae as follows: the episternal groove is ventrally inconspiscuous; the stipes, prementum and cardo are not very long; the second submarginal cell is not much shorter than the first; the setae on S2 and the other sterna are apparently not branched or plumose; the stigma is basal to vein r with margins apically diverging (this latter character is present in 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFCFA970AFC2FBA2A" box="[806,924,594,616]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Chilicolini">Chilicolini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFC00970AFA35BA2A" authority="Michener &amp; Rozen, 1999" authorityName="Michener &amp; Rozen" authorityYear="1999" box="[988,1414,594,616]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Geodiscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFC00970AFBE9BA25" box="[988,1114,594,615]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Geodiscelis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFBB8970AFA35BA2A" author="Michener CD &amp; Rozen JG" box="[1124,1414,594,616]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref6069" refString="Michener CD, Rozen JG. 1999. A new ground-nesting genus of xeromelissine bees from Argentina and the tribal classification of the subfamily (Hymenoptera: Colletidae). American Museum Novitates 3281: 1 - 10." type="journal article" year="1999">Michener &amp; Rozen, 1999</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFCF19729FBEEBAC4" author="Michener CD &amp; Rozen JG" box="[813,1117,625,647]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref6069" refString="Michener CD, Rozen JG. 1999. A new ground-nesting genus of xeromelissine bees from Argentina and the tribal classification of the subfamily (Hymenoptera: Colletidae). American Museum Novitates 3281: 1 - 10." type="journal article" year="1999">Michener &amp; Rozen, 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFBB39729FAB3BAC5" author="Engel MS" box="[1135,1280,625,647]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="1 - 11" refId="ref5550" refString="Engel MS. 2000. A new interpretation of the oldest Fossil Bee (Hymenoptera: Apidae). American Museum Novitates 3296: 1 - 11." type="journal article" year="2000">Engel, 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Therefore, 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFCFA97D7FBFEBAE7" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[806,1101,655,677]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFCFA97D7FBFEBAE7" box="[806,1101,655,677]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Palaeomacropis eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be considered as a Xeromelissinae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B86C36F9FFBAFFFDFCE39795FBEEBBD9" blockId="4.[806,1422,195,1904]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">
Specialized metasomal setae are also present on the metasoma in the halictid genus 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFB4497B3FCEEBB5D" authority="Cockerell 1919" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1919" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Homalictus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFB4497B3FAA8BB42" box="[1176,1307,747,768]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Homalictus</emphasis>
Cockerell 1919
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFCB39652FB70BB62" author="Alexander BA &amp; Michener CD" box="[879,1219,778,800]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="377 - 424" refId="ref5153" refString="Alexander BA, Michener CD. 1995. Phylogenetic studies of the families of short-tongued bees (Hymenoptera: Apoidea). University of Kansas Science Bulletin 55: 377 - 424." type="journal article" year="1995">Alexander &amp; Michener, 1995</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFB059652FAEFBB5D" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1919" box="[1241,1372,778,799]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Homalictus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFB059652FAEFBB5D" box="[1241,1372,778,799]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Homalictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFC439671FB91BB7C" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[927,1058,809,830]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFC439671FB91BB7C" box="[927,1058,809,830]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the enormous scopal hairs that it has on the sterna and the ventral part of the terga, and the plumose scopal hairs on its hind femora and tibia (
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFC4196DDFBE2BBD9" author="Michener CD" box="[925,1105,901,923]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" refId="ref5917" refString="Michener CD. 2000. The bees of the world. Baltimore, MD: The Johns Hopkins University Press." type="book" year="2000">Michener, 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F0C96572FFBAFFFDFCE396FCFAB6BE42" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" type="description">
<paragraph id="B86C36F9FFBAFFFDFCE396FCFAB6BE42" blockId="4.[806,1422,195,1904]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">
Among other groups, 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFBBC96FCFB50BBFB" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[1120,1251,932,953]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFBBC96FCFB50BBFB" box="[1120,1251,932,953]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from Andreninae due to its lack of paired subantennal sutures or facial foveae. It differs from the Oxaeinae (
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFCF196A7FC07BC57" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[813,948,1023,1045]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Andrenidae</taxonomicName>
) and Diphaglossinae (
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFB6296A7FA80BC57" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint Fargeau" authorityYear="1841" box="[1214,1331,1023,1045]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Colletidae</taxonomicName>
) in the presence of a stigma longer than the prestigma, with vein r arising well before the apical margin of the stigma, and the convex margin of the stigma in the marginal cell. 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFC0D9122FB4BBCD2" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[977,1272,1146,1168]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFC0D9122FB4BBCD2" box="[977,1272,1146,1168]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Palaeomacropis eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the Colletinae (
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFC3A91C1FBEDBCED" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint Fargeau" authorityYear="1841" box="[998,1118,1177,1199]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Colletidae</taxonomicName>
), Halictinae (
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFADB91C1FA32BCED" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1869" box="[1287,1409,1177,1199]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Halictidae</taxonomicName>
), and Nomioidinae (
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFC2391EFFBC4BC8F" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1869" box="[1023,1143,1207,1229]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Halictidae</taxonomicName>
) in its weak episternal groove, mainly dorsal and almost disappearing ventrally (this structure is also absent in the colletine 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFCFA904BFB23BD6B" authority="Michener, 1965" authorityName="Michener" authorityYear="1965" box="[806,1168,1299,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hesperocolletes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFCFA904BFC61BD6A" box="[806,978,1299,1320]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Hesperocolletes</emphasis>
Michener, 1965
</taxonomicName>
). The Nomiinae (
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFA87904BFCC0BD0A" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Halictidae</taxonomicName>
) also have a reduced episternal groove, as is the case in 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFC719009FB83BD24" authorityName="Michez &amp; Nel &amp; Menier &amp; Rasmont" authorityYear="2007" box="[941,1072,1361,1382]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFC719009FB83BD24" box="[941,1072,1361,1382]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Nevertheless, their marginal cell usually does not taper much toward the apex, unlike 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFCA790D7FB62BDE6" authority="(Michener, 2000)" baseAuthorityName="Michener" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[891,1233,1422,1444]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFCA790D7FC4DBDE6" box="[891,1022,1423,1444]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFBCF90D6FB79BDE6" author="Michener CD" box="[1043,1226,1422,1444]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" refId="ref5917" refString="Michener CD. 2000. The bees of the world. Baltimore, MD: The Johns Hopkins University Press." type="book" year="2000">Michener, 2000</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, although some nomiine species do have pointed marginal cells. The Nomiinae typically have a labrum with a strong apical process in the female, unlike 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFBA690B3FB4EBE42" baseAuthorityName="Michener" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[1146,1277,1515,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFBA690B3FB4EBE42" box="[1146,1277,1515,1536]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F0C96572FFBAFFFCFCE39351FDBCB8BA" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="706" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="B86C36F9FFBAFFFDFCE39351FCE1BEDB" blockId="4.[806,1422,195,1904]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">
Unlike 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFC499351FBAABE5C" baseAuthorityName="Michener" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[917,1049,1545,1566]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFC499351FBAABE5C" box="[917,1049,1545,1566]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the Baltic amber family 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFA9A9351FB87BE7F" authority="Engel, 2001" authorityName="Engel" authorityYear="2001" family="Palaeomelittidae" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" rank="family">
Palaeomelittidae 
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFC72937FFB87BE7F" author="Engel MS" box="[942,1076,1575,1597]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="1 - 192" refId="ref5578" refString="Engel MS. 2001. A monograph of the Baltic Amber bees and evolution of the Apoidea (Hymenoptera). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 259: 1 - 192." type="journal article" year="2001">Engel, 2001</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has no long, erect setae on the metasomal sterna. However it does have a well developed jugal lobe (
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBAFFFDFC3F933DFBDDBE39" author="Engel MS" box="[995,1134,1637,1659]" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" pagination="1 - 192" refId="ref5578" refString="Engel MS. 2001. A monograph of the Baltic Amber bees and evolution of the Apoidea (Hymenoptera). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 259: 1 - 192." type="journal article" year="2001">Engel, 2001</bibRefCitation>
), which 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFB13933DFAE1BE38" baseAuthorityName="Michener" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[1231,1362,1637,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFB13933DFAE1BE38" box="[1231,1362,1637,1658]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B86C36F9FFBAFFFCFCE393FAFDBCB8BA" blockId="4.[806,1422,195,1904]" lastBlockId="5.[162,778,195,401]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="706" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFCE393FAFBDABEFA" baseAuthorityName="Michener" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[831,1129,1698,1720]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFCE393FAFBDABEFA" box="[831,1129,1698,1720]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Palaeomacropis eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFB6893FAFA99BEFA" authorityName="Schenck" authorityYear="1860" box="[1204,1322,1698,1720]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Melittidae</taxonomicName>
are ST bees and they have in common the absence (or near absence) of episternal and scrobal grooves. Their jugal lobe (on the hindwing) is clearly shorter than the vannal lobe (characters shared with LT bees). The middle coxa of 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBAFFFDFCA29263FB11BF13" baseAuthorityName="Michener" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[894,1186,1851,1873]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBAFFFDFCA29263FB11BF13" box="[894,1186,1851,1873]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="705">Palaeomacropis eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is fully exposed laterally and nearly reaches the lower metapleural pit, as in contemporary species 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBBFFFCFE38959BFD85B89A" authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1802" box="[484,566,195,216]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Melitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBBFFFCFE38959BFD85B89A" box="[484,566,195,216]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="706">Melitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(character shared with LT bees) (
<bibRefCitation id="DC424B08FFBBFFFCFE9395BAFDB0B8BA" author="Michener CD" box="[335,515,226,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="706" refId="ref5917" refString="Michener CD. 2000. The bees of the world. Baltimore, MD: The Johns Hopkins University Press." type="book" year="2000">Michener, 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F0C96572FFBBFFFCFF679459FE78B9D3" pageId="5" pageNumber="706" type="description">
<paragraph id="B86C36F9FFBBFFFCFF679459FE78B9D3" blockId="5.[162,778,195,401]" pageId="5" pageNumber="706">
In conclusion, 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBBFFFCFEBC9459FE50B954" baseAuthorityName="Michener" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[352,483,257,278]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBBFFFCFEBC9459FE50B954" box="[352,483,257,278]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="706">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an ST bee, with a fully exposed middle coxa, without facial foveae or paired subantennal sutures, and with the jugal lobe shorter than the vannal lobe. Therefore, we include 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBBFFFCFF7E9424FE96B9D3" baseAuthorityName="Michener" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[162,293,380,401]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Palaeomacropis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eocenicus">
<emphasis id="8AA7EAEBFFBBFFFCFF7E9424FE96B9D3" box="[162,293,380,401]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="706">P. eocenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<taxonomicName id="7FD34D7AFFBBFFFCFE919423FE74B9D3" authorityName="Schenck" authorityYear="1860" box="[333,455,379,401]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Melittidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
